## Multivariate Analysis Effect size ($Zr$) and Out-of-sample predictions ($y_{i}$) 

Like the univariate models, the multivariate models did a poor job of explaining deviations from the meta-analytic mean. Because we pre-registered a multivariate model that contained collinear predictors that produce results which are not readily interpretable, we present these models in the supplement (@tbl-multivariate-models-mod-summary). The results of the multivariate analyses do not change the interpretations we present above based on the univariate analyses.

# Discussion

When a large pool of ecologists and evolutionary biologists analyzed the same two data sets to answer the same two questions, they produced substantially heterogeneous sets of answers. Although the variability in analytical outcomes was high for both datasets, the patterns of this variability differed distinctly between them. For the Blue Tit dataset, there was nearly continuous variability across a wide range of $Z_r$ values. In contrast, for the *Eucalyptus* dataset, there was less variability across most of the range, but more striking outliers at the tails. We investigated several hypotheses for drivers of this variability within datasets, but found little support for any of these. Most notably, even when we excluded analyses that had received one or more poor peer reviews, the heterogeneity in results largely persisted. Regardless of what drives the variability, the existence of such dramatically heterogeneous results when ecologists and evolutionary biologists seek to answer the same questions with the same data should trigger conversations about how ecologists and evolutionary biologists analyze data and interpret the results of their own analyses and those of others in the literature.

Our study provides compelling evidence that dramatic heterogeneity in analytical outcomes can result from the decisions of different individual analysts, however it provides only limited evidence to distinguish among hypotheses that might explain what drives this heterogeneity. We found that for the Blue Tit dataset, analysts variously described their results as showing no effect of sibling competition on growth, a mixed effect, or a negative effect. Similarly, their models mostly had negative $Z_r$ values though some showed no significant effect and three had negative $Z_r$ values. Out of sample predictions show For the *Eucalyptus* dataset, analysts variously described their results as showing positive, negative, mixed or no effects. Their models produced small $Z_r$ values that included significant positive, significant negative and non-significant results. Out of sample predictions show...

The registered analyses did not find that deviations from the meta-analytic mean by individual effect sizes ($Z_r$) or the predicted values of the dependent variable (y) were explained by peer-rating of each analysis team's method section, a measurement of the 'uniqueness' of the set of predictor variables included in each analysis, or whether the model included random effects. However, in our post-hoc analyses, we found that dropping analyses identified as unpublishable or in need of major revision by at least one reviewer modestly reduced the observed heterogeneity among the $Z_r$ outcomes for *Eucalyptus* analyses, but not among blue tit analyses. Further, dropping outlier values of $Z_r$ for *Eucalyptus* analyses, which had more extreme outliers, also led to a modest reduction in heterogeneity. When we examined the major outliers in the *Eucalyptus* data set, we found that they were associated with either substantial subsetting of the data, or averaging across large numbers of observations. Thus we have a plausible explanation for the outliers, and a hypothesis that, when analysts divide datasets into much smaller subsets, they are likely to observe divergent statistical effects.

Another likely partial explanation for the heterogeneity we observed is the lack of a precise relationship between the two research questions we posed and the data we provided. This lack of a precise relationship between data and question provides many opportunities for different model specifications, and so may inevitably lead to varied analytical outcomes [@auspurg2021]. However, we believe that the research questions we supplied are consistent with the kinds of research question that ecologists and evolutionary biologists typically work from. When designing the two research questions, we deliberately sought to represent the level of specificity we typically see in these disciplines. This level of specificity is evident when we look at the research questions posed by some recent meta-analyses in these fields:

-   "how \[does\] urbanisation impact mean phenotypic values and phenotypic variation ... \[in\] paired urban and non-urban comparisons of avian life-history traits" [@capilla-lasheras2022]

-   "\[what are\] the effects of ocean acidification on the crustacean exoskeleton, assessing both exoskeletal ion content (calcium and magnesium) and functional properties (biomechanical resistance and cuticle thickness)" [@siegel2022]

-   "\[what is\] the extent to which restoration affects both the mean and variability of biodiversity outcomes ... \[in\] terrestrial restoration" [@atkinson2022]

-   "\[does\] drought stress \[have\] a negative, positive, or null effect on aphid fitness" [@leybourne2021]

-   "\[what is\] the influence of nitrogen-fixing trees on soil nitrous oxide emissions" [@kou-giesbrecht2021]

There is not a single precise answer to any of these questions, nor to the questions we posed to analysts in our study. And this lack of a single clear answer will obviously continue to cause uncertainty since ecologists and evolutionary biologists conceive of the different answers from the different statistical models as all being answers to the same general question. A possible response would be a call to avoid these general questions in favor of much more precise alternatives. However, we suspect that ecologists and evolutionary biologists would continue to group these more precise questions into less concise groups that reflect the level of generality of interest to the research community.

Although variability in statistical outcomes among analysts may be inevitable, our results raise questions about why this variability differed between our two datasets. The forest plots from our two datasets show distinct patterns, and these differences are consistent with several alternative hypotheses. When regarding the standardized effect size ($Z_r$), the results submitted by analysts of the *Eucalyptus* dataset show a small average (close to zero) with most estimates close to zero (± 0.2), though some far enough above or below zero to cross the traditional threshold of statistical significance. There are a small number of striking outliers that are very far from zero. In contrast, the results submitted by analysts of the blue tit dataset show an average much further from zero (- 0.35) and a much greater spread among estimates across the range of $Z_r$ values (± 0.5 from the mean), with few modest outliers. So, a reasonable question to ask is, why is there more spread in effect size across the estimates that are not outliers in the blue tit analyses relative to the *Eucalyptus* analyses?

One possible explanation for the lower heterogeneity among most *Eucalyptus* effects is that weak relationships may limit the opportunities for heterogeneity in analytical outcome. Some evidence for this idea comes from two sets of "many labs" studies in psychology [@klein2014, @klein2018]. In these studies, many independent lab groups each replicated a large set of studies, including the experiment, data collection, and statistical analyses. These studies showed that, when the meta-analytic mean across the replications was small, there was much less heterogeneity among the outcomes than when the mean effect sizes were large [@klein2014, @klein2018]. Of course, a weak average effect size would not prevent divergent effects in all circumstances. For instance, among the *Eucalyptus* analyses, some took a radically smaller subset of the data and found dramatically divergent effect sizes.

Our observation that dramatic subsetting in the *Eucalyptus* data set was associated with correspondingly dramatic divergence in effect sizes leads us towards another hypothesis to explain the differences in heterogeneity between the *Eucalyptus* and blue tit analysis sets. It may be that when analysts often divide a dataset into subsets, the result will be greater heterogeneity in analytical outcome for that dataset. Although we saw subsetting associated with dramatic outliers in the *Eucalyptus* dataset, nearly all other analyses of *Eucalyptus* data used very close to the same set of 351 samples, and as we saw, these effects did not vary substantially. However, analysts often divided the blue tit data into subsets, and as we observed, sample sizes were much more variable among blue tit effects, and the effects themselves were also much more variable. Important to note here is that subsets of data may differ from each other for biological reasons, but they may also differ due to sampling error. Sampling error is, of course, a function of sample size, and sub-samples are, by definition, smaller samples, and so more subject to variability in effects due to sampling error.

Other features of datasets are also plausible candidates for driving heterogeneity in analytical outcomes, including features of covariates. For instance, if a covariate is strongly correlated with a dependent variable and uncorrelated with the primary independent variable, models with and without the covariate will differ dramatically because the proportion of residual variation explained by the independent variable will be much higher in the presence of the covariate. In contrast, if a covariate is correlated with the independent variable and the dependent variable, including the covariate will often weaken the relationship between the independent and dependent variable. This is because the proportion of the residual variable explained by the independent variable will be lower in the presence of the covariate. This collinearity between the covariate and independent variable could also create unexpected relationships as the distribution of residual variation remaining for the independent variable to explain after including the covariate could differ dramatically from the variability in the absence of the covariate. We are less confident regarding a role for covariates in explaining the differences between the blue tit and *Eucalyptus* data sets, but it may be that there were more covariates of substantial effect in the blue tit data set relative to the *Eucalyptus* dataset.

Although it is too early in the many-analyst research program to conclude which analytical decisions or which features of datasets are the most important drivers of heterogeneity in analytical outcomes, we must still grapple with the possibility that analytical outcomes may vary substantially based on the choices we make as analysts. If we assume that, at least sometimes, different analysts will produce dramatically different statistical outcomes, what should we do as ecologists and evolutionary biologists? We review some ideas below.

The easiest path forward would be to continue with business as usual. A case could be made for this path based on our results. For instance, among the Blue Tit analyses, the precise values of the estimated effects varied substantially, but the average effect was convincingly different from zero, and a majority of individual effects were of the same sign. Arguably, many ecologists and evolutionary biologists are primarily interested in the sign of a given effect and the corresponding p-value, and so the variability we observed when analyzing the blue tit dataset may not worry these researchers. Similarly, most effects from the *Eucalyptus* analyses are relatively close to zero, and approximately half of these effects do not cross the traditional threshold of statistically significantly different from zero. Therefore, a large proportion of people analyzing these data would conclude that there was no effect, and this is consistent with what we might conclude from the meta-analysis. However, we find the counter arguments to business-as-usual to be compelling. For blue tits, there is a substantial minority of effects that would be interpreted by many biologists as indicating the absence of an effect, and there are several effects that are actually opposite in sign to the average and cross the traditional threshold of statistical significance. Therefore, with some frequency, researchers would draw a conclusion distinctly different from the one we draw from the distribution as a whole. For the *Eucalyptus* analyses, this issue is more concerning. Considering their whole analysis process, around hlaf of analysis teams described there being no detectable relationship, with other responses spread between finding negative, positive and mixed relationships. Similarly, when considering statistical significance, approximately half of analyses would lead to conclusions that the effects differed from zero, but of these, about half would conclude the effect was positive, and the other half that the effect was negative.

Taken together, our results suggest to us that, where there is a diverse set of plausible analysis options, no single analysis should be considered a complete or reliable answer to a research question. Further, because there is strong evidence that ecologists and evolutionary biologists often present a biased subset of the analyses they conduct [@deressa2023, @yang2023], we don't expect that even a collection of different effect sizes from different studies will accurately represent the true distribution of effects. Therefore, we believe that an increased level of skepticism of the outcomes of single analyses, or even single meta-analyses, is warranted going forward.

If we are skeptical of single analyses, the path forward may be multiple analyses per dataset. One possibility is the traditional robustness or sensitivity check [e.g. @pei2020, @briga2021], in which the researcher presents several alternative versions of an analysis to demonstrate that the result is 'robust' [@lu2014]. Robustness checks are at risk of the same potential biases of reporting found in other studies [@silberzahn2018], especially given the relatively few models typically presented. However, these risks could be minimized by running more models and doing so with pre-registration or registered reports. Another option is model averaging. As most often practiced in ecology and evolutionary biology, model averaging involves first identifying a small suite of candidate models [see @burnham2002], then using Akaike weights, based on Akaike's Information Criterion (AIC), to calculate weighted averages for parameter estimates from those models. Again, the small number of models limits the exploration of specification space, but there is no reason to not examine more models. A more concerning limitation is that weighting by AIC may often be inconsistent with our modeling goals. AIC balances the tradeoff between model complexity and predictive ability, but penalizing models for complexity may not be suited for testing hypotheses about causation. So, AIC may often not offer the weight we want to use for an average, and we may also not wish to just generate an average. Instead, if we hope to understand an extensive universe of possible modeling outcomes, we could conduct a multiverse analysis, possibly with a specification curve. This would mean running In this case, we might run hundreds or thousands of models to examine the distribution of possible effects, and to see how different specification choices map onto these effects. However, there is a tradeoff between efficiently exploring large areas of specification space and limiting the analyses to biologically plausible specifications. Instead of simply identifying modeling decisions and creating all possible combinations for the multiverse, a researcher could attempt to prevent implausible combinations, though the more variables in the data set, the more difficult this becomes. To make this easier, one could recruit many analysts to each designate one or a few plausible specifications, as with our 'many analyst' model [@silberzahn2018]. An alternative that may be more labor intensive for the primary analyst, but which may lead to a more plausible set of models, could involve hypothesizing about causal pathways with DAGs to constrain the model set. Devoting this level of effort This sort of devotion of effort to thoughtful multiverse specifications, possibly combined with pre-registration to hinder undisclosed data dredging, seems worthy of consideration.

Although we have reviewed a variety of potential responses to the existence of variability in analytical outcomes, we certainly do not wish to imply that this is a comprehensive set of possible responses. Nor do we wish to imply that the opinions we have expressed are correct. Determining how the disciplines of ecology and evolutionary biology should respond to knowledge of the variability in analytical outcome will benefit from the contribution and discussion of ideas from across these disciplines. We look forward to learning from these discussions and to seeing how these disciplines ultimately respond.

Our results are consistent with a growing body of work exploring heterogeneity driven by analytical decisions. Much of this work has been in the quantitative social sciences (add references).. In all of these studies, when volunteers from the discipline analyzed the same data, they produced a worryingly diverse set of answers to a pre-set question. This diversity always included a wide range of effect sizes, and in most cases, even involved effects in opposite directions. Thus, our result should not be viewed as an anomalous outcome from two particular datasets, but instead as evidence from additional disciplines regarding the heterogeneity that can emerge from analyses of complex datasets to answer questions in probabilistic science. We should note, however, that our estimates of heterogeneity resulting from analytical choices are probably higher than is typical since they are higher than the averages found in meta-analyses combining studies that differ not only in analysts, but also in study system, data, and experimental methods [@senior2016].

Given our key result, that analytical outcomes can vary substantially depending on choices of analysts, we obviously must address the possibility that our own results and conclusions could be contingent on our analytical decisions. First, we do not claim (or believe) that our estimates of variability from analyses of these two data sets represent averages of the population of data sets in ecology and evolutionary biology. Ours is a sample of two and therefore can only demonstrate what is possible. We are most confident in our central conclusion that substantial heterogeneity in outcomes can emerge from analytical heterogeneity. Our confidence here is justified by the fact that this result does not derive from a complex analysis dependent on many modeling decisions. Instead, it derives from qualitative observations of our forest plots which contain patterns that result from a simple set of decisions that were mostly registered before data gathering. Results from our meta-regression models may be more contingent, but even here, we examined several scenarios which all show at least moderately similar patterns. We conducted analyses with different subsets of data and for the blue tit analyses, we always observed very similar estimates of variability across these different subsets. For *Eucalyptus* analyses, the results were qualitatively similar, but the level of heterogeneity varied, with a modestly lower $I^2$ value in the subset from which outliers were excluded.

## to the supplement

We created two different sets of data with different degrees of conservatism in our exclusion coded, the first dataset excluded analyses according to our preregistered exclusion rules, while the second dataset was generated with more stringent exclusion rules after manually checking the submitted results of all analyses (@tbl-Zr-exclusion-subsetting). Different degrees of conservatism in excluding analyses had minimal impact on the meta-analytic mean for both blue tit and *Eucalyptus* analyses, regardless of whether outliers were excluded (@tbl-Zr-exclusion-subsetting). However, applying conservative and additioanl exclusions to the blue tit analyses did shift the amount of total heterogeneity apportioned among between-`TeamIdentifier` differences and between-`study_id` differences, a greater amount of heterogeneity being driven by between-`TeamIdentifier` differences ( $I^2_{TeamIdentifier} =$ 40.11%, $I^2_{TeamIdentifier,study\_id} =$ 57.63% under conservative exclusions, $I^2_{TeamIdentifier} =$ 38.42%, $I^2_{TeamIdentifier,study\_id} =$ 59.35% under further exclusions, @tbl-Zr-exclusion-subsetting)
